Multiple sclerosis prevalence rises with latitude on both sides of the equator (
 Ascherio and Schwarzschild, 2016; 
 Sintzel 
  et al., 2018
 ), and migration studies suggest that multiple sclerosis risk is heavily influenced by environmental factors (
 Berg-Hansen and Celius, 2015; 
 Ascherio and Munger, 2016; 
 Dobson and Giovannoni, 2019). This is thought to occur because ultraviolet light stimulates vitamin D production in the skin, and vitamin D levels are inversely correlated with multiple sclerosis risk (
 Sintzel 
  et al., 2018
 ).
